d migrants have become the ‘new poor’. Combining theoretical and empirical tools, this is a topical fresh take on the understanding of poverty in Italy that is even more crucial considering the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPovertyzItaly. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aBenassi, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMorlicchio, Enrica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831111967180 cprintz978144735221140uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447352228?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447352228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447352228/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles